hook.real_world_problem:
Look at every array-based class you've written in Modules 3-5:

```java
class Library {
    private Book[] books;    // fixed size
    private int count;        // must track manually

    public Library(int capacity) {
        books = new Book[capacity];  // must guess right size
        count = 0;
    }

    public void addBook(Book b) {
        if (count < books.length) {  // must check — what if full?
            books[count++] = b;
        }
    }

    public Book[] getBooks() {
        return Arrays.copyOf(books, count);  // defensive copy!
    }
}
```

Five problems:
1. **Fixed capacity** — guess wrong and you can't add more books
2. **Manual count** — forget to increment, or increment wrong, and it's a bug
3. **Null slots** — `books[count]` through `books.length-1` are null and must never be accessed
4. **Removal is painful** — you have to shift elements manually
5. **Defensive copies** — needed everywhere

Now watch this:

```java
class Library {
    private List<Book> books = new ArrayList<>();

    public void addBook(Book b) { books.add(b); }
    public void removeBook(Book b) { books.remove(b); }
    public List<Book> getBooks() { return books; }
    public int bookCount() { return books.size(); }
}
```

No capacity. No count. No null slots. No shifts. No defensive copies. Just clean, readable code.

Welcome to `ArrayList` — your new default data structure.

concept_explanation.intro:
**ArrayList** is a resizable array — it grows automatically as you add elements. It's part of the Java Collections Framework and lives in `java.util`.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

// Declare
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

// Add
names.add("Aisha");
names.add("Raj");
names.add("Priya");

// Size
System.out.println(names.size());    // 3

// Access by index
System.out.println(names.get(0));    // "Aisha"
System.out.println(names.get(2));    // "Priya"

// Modify
names.set(1, "Vikram");              // replace index 1

// Remove
names.remove("Raj");                 // remove by value
names.remove(0);                     // remove by index

// Iterate
for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println(name);
}
```

Three things to note immediately:
- `List<String>` — declaring with the INTERFACE type (programming to interfaces from Topic 5.4)
- `<String>` — generics, tells the list what type it holds
- `new ArrayList<>()` — `<>` is the diamond operator, type is inferred

concept_explanation.core_methods:
**ArrayList's essential API**:

```java
List<String> list = new ArrayList<>();

// Adding
list.add("first");            // appends to end
list.add(0, "zeroth");        // insert at index — shifts others right
list.addAll(otherList);       // append all from another collection

// Reading
String s = list.get(0);       // get by index (0-based)
int n = list.size();           // number of elements
boolean empty = list.isEmpty(); // equivalent to list.size() == 0

// Checking
boolean found = list.contains("Aisha");  // linear search using .equals()
int i = list.indexOf("Raj");            // first index, -1 if not found

// Modifying
list.set(1, "updated");        // replace element at index
String removed = list.remove(0);  // remove by index, returns removed
boolean didRemove = list.remove("name"); // remove first occurrence by value
list.clear();                   // remove all elements

// Sublist
List<String> sub = list.subList(1, 3);  // elements at index 1, 2 (exclusive end)

// Convert to array
String[] arr = list.toArray(new String[0]);
```

**Key detail on remove**: `list.remove(1)` removes the element at INDEX 1. `list.remove("text")` removes the first element EQUAL TO 'text'. When the list holds Integers, `list.remove(1)` is ambiguous — use `list.remove(Integer.valueOf(1))` to remove by value.

concept_explanation.iterating:
Three ways to iterate an ArrayList (in order of preference):

**1. Enhanced for-each (preferred for simple iteration)**:
```java
for (String name : names) {
    System.out.println(name);
}
```

**2. Index-based for loop (when you need the index)**:
```java
for (int i = 0; i < names.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(i + ": " + names.get(i));
}
```

**3. forEach with lambda (Java 8+, covered in Streams module)**:
```java
names.forEach(name -> System.out.println(name));
// Or with method reference:
names.forEach(System.out::println);
```

**⚠️ Don't modify while iterating with for-each** — ConcurrentModificationException:
```java
// WRONG — throws ConcurrentModificationException
for (String name : names) {
    if (name.startsWith("A")) names.remove(name);
}

// RIGHT — iterate by index backwards, or collect then remove
for (int i = names.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    if (names.get(i).startsWith("A")) names.remove(i);
}
// Or: use removeIf (Java 8+)
names.removeIf(name -> name.startsWith("A"));
```

concept_explanation.list_interface:
Always declare as `List<T>`, not `ArrayList<T>` — programming to the interface:

```java
// WRONG: bound to ArrayList
ArrayList<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

// RIGHT: programmed to List interface
List<String> names = new ArrayList<>();

// Later can swap to LinkedList with ONE change:
List<String> names = new LinkedList<>();  // works everywhere
```

Benefits covered in Topic 5.4 — flexibility, testability, decoupling. Apply it automatically.

**Method signatures** — take List, not ArrayList:

```java
// Flexible — works with any List implementation
public void printAll(List<String> items) { ... }

// Restrictive — only ArrayList
public void printAll(ArrayList<String> items) { ... }
```

This is the most important daily habit from Topic 5.4: `List<T>` everywhere you declare, `new ArrayList<>()` when you create.

concept_explanation.sorting_arraylist:
Sort an ArrayList:

```java
import java.util.Collections;

List<String> names = new ArrayList<>(Arrays.asList("Raj", "Aisha", "Priya"));
Collections.sort(names);         // ascending (uses natural Comparable order)

List<Product> products = new ArrayList<>();
// ...
Collections.sort(products);                      // uses Product's Comparable
Collections.sort(products, ProductSorter.BY_NAME);  // uses Comparator
// or:
products.sort(ProductSorter.BY_NAME);            // List.sort() — same effect
```

`Collections.sort` and `list.sort` both work. `list.sort(comparator)` is the more modern style (Java 8+).

**Collections utility class** has many more methods (covered fully in Topic 6.5): `Collections.min`, `Collections.max`, `Collections.shuffle`, `Collections.reverse`, etc.

concept_explanation.arraylist_of_objects:
ArrayList shines with objects:

```java
List<Product> catalog = new ArrayList<>();
catalog.add(new Product("Mouse", 599.0));
catalog.add(new Product("Keyboard", 1999.0));
catalog.add(new Product("Monitor", 18999.0));

// Direct access
Product p = catalog.get(0);  // returns Product object
System.out.println(p.getName());

// Search (uses Product.equals() — from Topic 4.4!)
Product target = new Product("Mouse", 599.0);
boolean found = catalog.contains(target);  // uses equals()
int idx = catalog.indexOf(target);

// Remove (uses equals())
catalog.remove(target);

// Iterate and process
double total = 0;
for (Product prod : catalog) {
    total += prod.getPrice();
}
System.out.println("Total: ₹" + total);
```

This is why Topic 4.4 (equals/hashCode) matters — `contains()` and `remove()` use `.equals()` to find elements. Without proper equals(), these methods don't work correctly.

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
import java.util.Objects;

class Book {
    private final String isbn;
    private String title;
    private String author;
    private boolean available;

    public Book(String isbn, String title, String author) {
        this.isbn = isbn;
        this.title = title;
        this.author = author;
        this.available = true;
    }

    public String getIsbn() { return isbn; }
    public String getTitle() { return title; }
    public String getAuthor() { return author; }
    public boolean isAvailable() { return available; }
    public void checkOut() { available = false; }
    public void returnBook() { available = true; }

    @Override
    public boolean equals(Object o) {
        if (!(o instanceof Book b)) return false;
        return Objects.equals(isbn, b.isbn);  // books equal by ISBN
    }

    @Override public int hashCode() { return Objects.hash(isbn); }

    @Override public String toString() {
        return '"' + title + '"' + " by " + author + (available ? " [Available]" : " [Checked Out]");
    }
}
```

Book has proper equals by ISBN. This means `library.contains(book)` and `library.remove(book)` will work correctly.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.List;

class Library {
    private final String name;
    private final List<Book> books = new ArrayList<>();

    public Library(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    // Add — no capacity check, no count++
    public void addBook(Book book) {
        books.add(book);
    }

    // Remove by book object — uses Book.equals()
    public boolean removeBook(Book book) {
        return books.remove(book);
    }

    // Find by title — iterate and check
    public Book findByTitle(String title) {
        for (Book b : books) {
            if (b.getTitle().equalsIgnoreCase(title)) {
                return b;
            }
        }
        return null;
    }

    // Get only available books
    public List<Book> getBooksInStock() {
        List<Book> available = new ArrayList<>();
        for (Book b : books) {
            if (b.isAvailable()) {
                available.add(b);
            }
        }
        return available;
    }

    // Sort by title
    public void sortByTitle() {
        books.sort((a, b) -> a.getTitle().compareTo(b.getTitle()));
    }

    public int size() { return books.size(); }

    public void printAll() {
        System.out.println("=== " + name + " (" + books.size() + " books) ===");
        for (Book b : books) {
            System.out.println("  " + b);
        }
    }
}
```

Every method is clean. No count tracking. No null checks. No capacity issues.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    Library lib = new Library("Hyderabad City Library");

    Book b1 = new Book("ISBN-001", "Dune", "Frank Herbert");
    Book b2 = new Book("ISBN-002", "Foundation", "Isaac Asimov");
    Book b3 = new Book("ISBN-003", "1984", "George Orwell");
    Book b4 = new Book("ISBN-004", "Clean Code", "Robert Martin");

    lib.addBook(b1);
    lib.addBook(b2);
    lib.addBook(b3);
    lib.addBook(b4);

    lib.printAll();

    // Check out some books
    b1.checkOut();
    b3.checkOut();

    System.out.println("\nIn stock: " + lib.getBooksInStock().size());
    for (Book b : lib.getBooksInStock()) {
        System.out.println("  " + b);
    }

    // Find by title
    Book found = lib.findByTitle("foundation");  // case-insensitive
    System.out.println("\nFound: " + found);

    // Sort and print
    lib.sortByTitle();
    System.out.println("\nSorted:");
    lib.printAll();

    // Remove a book
    lib.removeBook(b2);
    System.out.println("\nAfter removing Foundation: " + lib.size() + " books");
}
```

